---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { MapPin, Globe, Calendar } from 'lucide-astro';

const KUBECON_SCHED_URL = 'https://sched.co/2DY82';
const COZYSUMMIT_URL = 'https://community.cncf.io/events/details/cncf-virtual-project-events-hosted-by-cncf-presents-cozysummit-virtual-2026/';
const YT_EMBED = 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/X3sUAsTPbDM';
const YT_URL = 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X3sUAsTPbDM';
---

<Layout title="Talks" description="Public talks on Reverse GitOps — the API-first, Git-recorded platform operating model.">
  <main class="page-main">
    <div class="page-content">
      <h1 class="page-title">Talks</h1>

      <section>
        <h2 class="section-label">Upcoming</h2>
        <div class="talk-card">
          <div class="talk-meta">
            <span class="talk-event">CozySummit Virtual 2026</span>
            <span class="talk-sep">·</span>
            <Globe size={13} style="flex-shrink:0;opacity:0.7" />
            <span class="talk-date">Virtual · May 26, 2026 · 17:50–18:20 UTC</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="talk-title">What If Every Cozystack Change Became a Commit?</h3>
          <p class="talk-desc">
            Cozystack exposes platform services as Kubernetes API resources — Postgres, Redis,
            Bucket, Kubernetes. Users interact in the usual ways: kubectl, the Cozystack
            dashboard, or AI agents via MCP. But who is making all these changes, and why did
            they do it? Git seems far away. But it doesn't have to be.
          </p>
          <p class="talk-desc">
            What if every platform change automatically appeared as clean YAML in Git? Fully
            automated — a silent layer that turns API activity into a durable, readable history
            of infrastructure intent. Instead of digging through logs or dashboards, teams get
            versioned history they can inspect, diff, and share. The platform continuously writes
            its intent back to Git. Git stops being the interface — and starts being the memory.
          </p>
          <div class="talk-links">
            <a href={COZYSUMMIT_URL} class="talk-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Register free →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="section-label">Past</h2>
        <div class="talk-card">
          <div class="talk-meta">
            <span class="talk-event">KubeCon + CloudNativeCon Europe 2026 · Platform Engineering Day</span>
            <span class="talk-sep">·</span>
            <MapPin size={13} style="flex-shrink:0;opacity:0.7" />
            <span class="talk-date">Amsterdam · March 23, 2026</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="talk-title">The GitOps Paradox: Why Your Devs Need an API You Don't Want To Build</h3>
          <p class="talk-desc">
            This session argues that GitOps is valuable, but Git does not always need to be the
            human-facing front door for every change. Platform teams often end up rebuilding APIs
            and UIs around workflows that the Kubernetes API already models well. Reverse GitOps
            explores a different approach: use a small, typed Kubernetes control plane for user
            intent, then write that intent back into Git so review, promotion, and auditability
            stay intact.
          </p>
          <p class="talk-desc">
            The talk includes two live demos: a simple application writing user intent into the
            Kubernetes API and syncing it back to Git; and a higher-level platform resource
            flowing from API input to Git to preview and production deployment.
          </p>
          <div class="talk-video-wrap">
            <iframe
              src={YT_EMBED}
              title="The GitOps Paradox — KubeCon Platform Engineering Day 2026"
              allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
              allowfullscreen
            ></iframe>
          </div>
          <div class="talk-links">
            <a href={YT_URL} class="talk-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Watch on YouTube →</a>
            <a href={KUBECON_SCHED_URL} class="talk-link secondary" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Session page</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
